included.description:
As part of a cross-functional team, I focused on simplifying the process of setting up Collaboration systems (phones, video, voice mail, auto attendant, etc.) especially for organizations with 50-500 users. 

Here are a few of the design research projects I led in this role: 

â Initiated customer experience journey project. Led engineers, marketers, and product managers in mapping the end-to-end journey for Cisco Partners as they market, sell, install and support a specific product line. Discovered major pain point in handoff from installation to technical support; this insight led to new collaboration between these departments and a new focus on troubleshooting tools. 

â Identified usability flaws in prototype of installation automation tool. Ran five 90-minute research sessions with Cisco-certified engineers and ranked each screen as red (major problems), yellow (minor concerns), or green (clear approval). Guided design and engineering teams through next steps for design, documentation, and integrations. 

â Established hierarchy of tasks. Recruited office managers for a mixed-method study (cardsorting, rapid prototyping, and one-on-one interviews via videoconference) to inform functionality of a new software tool that enables the âfake IT personâ (as one interviewee described her role) to make changes to company phone systems. 

This research fueled Cisco's competitive advantage and future growth.

included.summary:
I lead teams through the process of gaining a deeper understanding of the people who use their products. This research is all about highlighting opportunities and reducing uncertainty throughout the journey of designing experiences. 

Whether Iâm interviewing users to understand their needs, or running usability tests to assess how well new designs are meeting these needs, itâs fascinating to learn about the specific tools and workarounds that people use to do their jobs. I work closely with designers, engineers and product managers to bring these insights to life. 

I moved back to San Francisco (my hometown!) in 2014 after 8 years in Chile and China, where I worked with a wide range of startups, universities and global brands. Most recently in Chile, I taught entrepreneurship classes from the perspective of design thinking and user experience. This inspired me to immerse myself in the world of user experience research and design. 

I'm passionate about women's health. And a big believer in writing things out by hand. And I love chatting with students!
included.headline: User Experience Researcher at Workday

included.name: The Secret to Creativity and Productivity
included.description:
Do you ever find yourself thinking, âWell, I could move to San Francisco, or New York, or China, or Chile! And I could work in tech, or fashion, or marketing, or something else!â while another voice in your head says, âThis is my list of things to do today. I need to go buy groceries, book a bus ticket for tomorrowâs trip, follow up with Joe from the conferenceâ¦ â

In my experience, holding these two types of thoughtsâbig picture ideas and day-to-day detailsâin my mind at the same time leads to major stress. And in a recent class on creativity, I learned why: They require different types of thinking, which come from different rhythms inside your brain. So the good news: Itâs not just you.

included.name: Working Abroad? How to Give a Presentation in the Local Language
included.description:
Even if youâve been working abroad for a while, and you feel comfortable getting around the city and chatting with colleagues, thereâs something incredibly intimidating about being invited to give a formal presentation in your second (or third) language. 

Take it from me: The first week I landed in Chile as part of a government-backed entrepreneurship program, a professor invited me to a faculty meeting to speak about Silicon Valley and how academics could participate in entrepreneurship through technology transfer programs. Though I grew up in the heart of Silicon Valley, was familiar with the entrepreneurship scene, and spoke fluent Spanish, I wasnât sure how to start creating a presentation for a totally foreign audience from scratch.
